Here's the typical registration pattern:

```csharp
public static class MauiProgram
{
    public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
    {
        var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
        builder.UseMauiApp<App>();

        // Data service — one shared HttpClient/state across the app
        builder.Services.AddSingleton<IDataService, DataService>();

        // ViewModels — new instance per navigation so each page gets fresh state
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainViewModel>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailViewModel>();

        // Pages — transient so each navigation push creates a new page
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainPage>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailPage>();

        return builder.Build();
    }
}
```

**Why these lifetimes:**

| Registration | Lifetime | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| `IDataService` | **Singleton** | Wraps `HttpClient` and shared state (caches, auth tokens). One instance avoids socket exhaustion and keeps state consistent. |
| ViewModels | **Transient** | Each page navigation should get a fresh VM so stale data from a previous visit doesn't leak through. |
| Pages | **Transient** | MAUI creates a new page per navigation push; a singleton page would re-use old bindings and visual state. |

**When you'd change this:**

- Use **`AddScoped`** for ViewModels if you use `Shell` navigation with scoped service providers (less common).
- Use **singleton** for a ViewModel only if it backs a tab that must survive tab switches (e.g., a shopping cart).
- If `DataService` is cheap and stateless, transient works too — but singleton is the safer default for anything holding an `HttpClient`.
